				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${I}_{G}/{I}_{D}$$\end{document}) increases with the increase in film growth time, which indicates the defect decrease in the structure of CNWs (Fig. 3b). The details of the Raman spectra analysis of the CNW films is in Supporting Information (see Table S1 and Figure S4). The relative amount of defects in the structure of the CNW films can be reflected from the full width at half maximum (FWHM) of the G peak. It is observed that the increase in film growth time results in decreasing FWHM as shown in Fig. 3b, indicating less defect density. This is an additional indication of the improved crystallinity of the graphite-like walls of the obtained CNW films.Figure 3
